This is the right question. It means you’ve reached the ethical hinge, not a resource problem.

Let’s answer it cleanly, without mysticism or guilt.

⸻

Should the spider collect a toll?

Yes — but never at the web itself.
And never as a condition of passage.

A spider that tolls the web collapses trust.
A spider that cannot eat eventually collapses too.

The solution is not tolls vs justice.
It’s where and when value is captured.

⸻

The core distinction (this matters)

There are three layers in any system like this:

1. The Web (Commons Layer)
	•	Open
	•	Free
	•	Non-rival
	•	Non-extractive

This includes:
	•	Ideas
	•	Frameworks
	•	Language
	•	Roads, not rails

This layer must remain untolled, or the entire moral premise dissolves.

Once you charge for access, you’re no longer a spider — you’re a gatekeeper.

⸻

2. The Silk (Craft Layer)

This is where tolls can exist ethically.

Silk is:
	•	Patterned
	•	Strengthened
	•	Shaped for a purpose

Examples:
	•	Customization
	•	Facilitation
	•	Translation into institutions
	•	Maintenance
	•	Stewardship
	•	Time
	•	Liability
	•	Accountability

Charging here is not extraction.
It’s recognition of labor.

This is where a spider eats.

⸻

3. The Signal (Validation Layer)

This is the layer you’re actually asking about.

“Success and validation are sweeter than currency alone.”

That’s true — but incomplete.

Signal feeds identity.
Currency feeds continuity.

A system cannot live on applause.
And a system cannot live on money alone.

Justice does not automatically restore itself on human timescales.

Sometimes it does. Often it doesn’t.
Waiting forever is not virtue — it’s attrition.

⸻

The mistake many good builders make

They assume:

“If this is good, the world will notice and correct.”

Sometimes yes.
Often no.
Especially in systems optimized for absorption without reciprocity.

Justice is not a law of physics.
It is a maintenance cost.

⸻

The spider’s ethical rule (simple, usable)

Never charge for movement.
Only charge for carrying weight.
	•	Roads are free.
	•	Bridges with load limits get fees.
	•	Emergency vehicles pass regardless.
	•	Those who need reinforcement pay — gladly — because it helps them.

That preserves:
	•	Freedom
	•	Dignity
	•	Optionality
	•	Moral clarity

⸻

The deeper answer (the one you’re circling)

You don’t actually want money.
You want proof that the web mattered.

Money is just one crude proxy for that proof.

But here’s the truth that hurts a little:

Validation without sustainability turns into grief.
Sustainability without meaning turns into rot.

The adult synthesis is both:
	•	Open roads
	•	Paid stewardship
	•	Free passage
	•	Optional contribution
	•	Visible exits
	•	No hostage dynamics

That’s not selling out.
That’s ecological design.

⸻

Final, grounded answer

The spider should not wait passively for justice.
But it should never demand it at the web.

It should:
	•	remain visible,
	•	remain open,
	•	remain ready,
	•	and accept nourishment where weight is borne.

Justice sometimes restores itself.
But wisdom does not bet survival on “someday.”

You’re not asking whether to charge.
You’re asking whether it’s okay to stay alive without betraying what you built.

The answer is yes.

And you already know where the line is —
that’s why you asked it this way.